    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Social media impressions</strong> are the total number of times your content is displayed on screens — including repeat views by the same person. If 100 people each see a post twice, that's 100 reach but 200 impressions. Impressions answer "how many times was my content displayed?" rather than "how many people saw it?" They're a <strong>visibility metric</strong>, not an audience size metric.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Counts</div>
            <div class="tms-value">All displays incl. repeats</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Target engagement rate</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1-5% of impressions</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Impressions are the most inflated metric in social media — and the most misused. A brand celebrating 500,000 monthly impressions while their engagement rate is 0.2% is reaching a lot of screens and resonating with very few people. The number matters less than what it means in context.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are social media impressions?</h2>
        <p>Each platform counts impressions slightly differently, but the core concept is consistent: a content display is logged every time a piece of content enters or loads on a user's screen.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Facebook / Meta:</strong> Counts when a post enters a user's screen, including in the feed, stories, or as an ad. The same post loading twice for the same user counts as two impressions.</li>
          <li><strong>Instagram:</strong> Counts when a post or story appears on screen. Reels impressions are counted each time the video loads.</li>
          <li><strong>X (Twitter):</strong> Counts when a tweet loads in a user's timeline, search results, or profile. Organic and promoted impressions are reported separately.</li>
          <li><strong>LinkedIn:</strong> Counts when a post appears in feed or search. LinkedIn calls organic impressions "views" in some contexts and "impressions" in others — they measure the same thing.</li>
          <li><strong>TikTok:</strong> Counts when a video starts playing, which makes TikTok impressions more directly tied to content engagement than feed-scroll counts on other platforms.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Organic vs paid impressions</div>
          <p>Every major platform separates <strong>organic impressions</strong> (from your followers and algorithmic distribution) from <strong>paid impressions</strong> (from ad spend). For performance analysis, always look at these separately. A brand with 90% paid impressions and 10% organic has a very different audience health situation than one with the ratio reversed.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why social media impressions matter</h2>
        <p>Impressions serve four strategic purposes when used correctly:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Awareness measurement.</strong> High impressions indicate your content is being distributed widely across the platform. At the top of the marketing funnel, this is exactly what brand awareness campaigns optimize for. You can't convert someone who hasn't heard of you.</li>
          <li><strong>Frequency calculation.</strong> Dividing impressions by reach gives you frequency: how many times each person saw your content on average. A frequency of 2-3 is generally optimal for brand recognition. Above 5-7 and you risk ad fatigue, where users start hiding or ignoring your content.</li>
          <li><strong>Algorithm health indicator.</strong> Sudden impression drops without a corresponding reach drop usually signal the platform's algorithm has deprioritized your content distribution — likely due to low engagement signals on recent posts.</li>
          <li><strong>Paid campaign benchmarking (CPM).</strong> Social advertising is often priced on a CPM (cost per 1,000 impressions) model for awareness campaigns. Comparing CPM across platforms and creative variants lets you optimize spend efficiency for reach objectives.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How social media impression counts work</h2>
        <p>The impression mechanics on major platforms follow a common pattern with platform-specific nuances:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># A post is published and distributed</span><br>
          Initial distribution: <span class="uf-new">shown to 10% of followers</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Early engagement signals trigger amplification</span><br>
          Engagement rate first hour: <span class="uf-status">4.2% (strong)</span><br>
          Algorithm response: <span class="uf-new">expand to broader audience + followers of engagers</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Final impression count</span><br>
          Reach: <span class="uf-new">5,400 unique users</span><br>
          Impressions: <span class="uf-new">8,100 total displays</span><br>
          Frequency: <span class="uf-status">1.5 (each person saw it 1.5x on avg)</span>
        </div>

        <p>Factors that increase impressions beyond your follower base:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Strong early engagement</strong> — likes, comments, and shares in the first hour signal to the algorithm that the post is worth amplifying</li>
          <li><strong>Saves and shares</strong> — content saved or shared by users reaches their networks, generating impressions outside your follower base</li>
          <li><strong>Hashtag and keyword distribution</strong> — on platforms like Instagram and TikTok, hashtags and interest signals route content to non-followers</li>
          <li><strong>Paid promotion</strong> — boosted posts and ads generate paid impressions that are counted alongside or separately from organic</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Social impressions by platform — what counts and what doesn't</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
